Alice Saltzman sees her part-time job as a mission .
By working with medical students , she hopes to make one of the most uncomfortable aspects of medicine a gentler , less intimidating process _ for both patient and doctor .
A New York social worker turned actress , Ms. Saltzman , 36 , and her colleagues around the country are playing an increasingly important role in medical education .
Called genital teaching associates , or GTAs , they use their bodies as models to teach breast , pelvic and genital-urinary examination techniques to medical students , residents and even doctors .
`` When I was a social worker , I became very concerned about how women were treated , '' Ms. Saltzman said .
When she learned about the associates through a colleague who was in the field , she became curious .
`` I wasn n't sure I was going to be able to do it .
But now , I feel like I 'm helping women all over the world .
It 's very empowering . ''
Some days , she said , `` I come home feeling like I 've done such a world of good . ''
Since being introduced in the 1970s , teaching associate programs have expanded to nearly half the nation 's medical schools , if not more , said Gayle Gliva-McConvey , a pioneer in the programs and the director of the professional skills center at Eastern Virginia Medical School in Norfolk .
Such programs are reaching more and more students , in effect changing the way the intimate examinations are conducted , one fledgling doctor at a time .
Now , in the era of managed care , the associate 's role has become even more important , as health care companies closely guard their doctors ' hours , said Ms. Gliva-McConvey .
But the greater service is provided by helping to train more nurses , doctors and other practitioners to handle one of the most stressful parts of patient examinations _ and in fact to conduct genital examinations at all .
Men and women are involved in associate programs , but the emphasis has always been on women .
`` It was pretty clear we were doing a pretty terrible job teaching medical students how to do pelvic exams , '' said Dr. Robert Kretzschmar , now in private practice in Iowa City , Iowa .
Teaching was done at clinics on indigent patients who had no choice by `` terrified medical students looking at female genitalia on a live person for the first time , '' Kretzschmar recalled from the early 1960s when he was an assistant professor of obstetrics and gynecology at the University of Iowa .
A few years later , Kretzschmar sowed the seeds of the nation 's `` standardized patient '' programs , using average people to pose as patients for medical students .
He started teaching medical interviewing techniques to his students using the wives of fellow staff physicians at the University of Iowa .
By the late 1960s , he had made the leap to the genital teaching associates , employing an aide from the urology department who had agreed to be a model for pelvic exams .
She requested to be draped so she could remain anonymous .
`` The person was being paid , and not exploited , '' he said , unlike the disadvantaged women at the clinic .
`` It was a great improvement , '' he added .
But it still was not what he wanted : `` I wanted to get rid of the drape .
I wanted the patient to interact with the students . ''
At professional meetings throughout the 1970s , he explained his program and the idea took off , he said .
One medical school hired prostitutes for its program .
Others placed ads in local newspapers .
Kretzschmar , though , set about finding bright women who were good teachers and who wanted to contribute to medical education .
He offered $ 25 an hour .
`` These people could do a better job of teaching than I , because they were using their own anatomy , '' he said .
The genital teaching associate programs evolved with the standardized patient programs , which now exist in 83 of the nation 's 126 medical schools , according to Ms. Gliva-McConvey , up from 69 programs in 1991 - 92 .
Exact figures are not available on the number of genital teaching associate programs , but anecdotal reports indicate a strong presence .
At the University of Arkansas for Medical Sciences in Little Rock , for example , both programs have grown significantly , said Mary Cantrell , who was an actress and a standardized patient before become director of the school 's clinical skills center .
In 1993 , the school had one standardized patient .
Today , it has more than 200 , including 30 genital teaching associates .
`` The impact it has on students and the amount of doctor time it saves is amazing , '' she said .
`` These medical students can end up doing a better exam than a practicing nurse or physician . ''
