Even after years with the books and the lectures , many medical students admit they are hardly prepared for their first genital exam .
When confronted with their first naked patient they have been known to faint , cry , vomit , become hysterical and sweat .
If they don n't overcome those reactions while working with an associate , they could experience them with an actual patient .
`` All a student 's folkways , all their traditions are being challenged , '' said Cathey Bienkowski , who has coordinated associate programs in the New York City area since 1982 .
`` We are what we have been brought up to be .
We all have certain values about nudity and touching .
The whole class is set up to be safe for the student . ''
Added Josie Hasle , a retired associate who set up the program at the University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey at Newark : `` It 's such an invasive exam .
And everyone who walks through the door has baggage .
We help them move it from the personal to the clinical . ''
Beginning at Louisiana State University , she since has managed the programs at Tulane , campuses of the University of Texas , the University of Alabama and the State University of New York , among others .
With the associates , she said , `` The student gets a nonthreatening teaching environment . ''
Dr. Mark Swartz , director of the Morchand Center for Clinical Competence at Mount Sinai School of Medicine , where students from six New York medical schools practice clinical skills , said that the reluctance of doctors to perform routine pelvic examinations needs to be addressed .
`` If you compare the average 25-year-old medical student to the 25-year-old in public relations , '' he said , `` they are very immature .
Medical students have had much more of a sheltered social background than non-medical students .
From college they 've been so directed toward their career that , in many cases , their social development has been less , and with fewer interactions .
They could be very good at science but they haven n't begun to pass interpersonal skills 101 . ''
That makes such programs even more necessary , said Dr. Lila Wallis , a past president of the American Medical Women 's Association and founder of Cornell University 's associate program .
`` It is every woman 's right to have a painless , competent , sensitive and communicative exam , '' she said .
`` A woman with an unpleasant one in her past means that she won n't go for check-ups and jeopardizes her health . ''
Dr. Wallis , an internist , is particularly incensed with doctors who do not perform them .
`` A breast and pelvic is just as integral to the exam of a woman as an exam of the mouth , throat , lungs , heart , abdomen and extremities is .
Everything is intertwined in the body .
To separate it out is diagnostically invalid . ''
Although the associate programs work in different ways , depending on the school , the model that Ms. Saltzman follows is among the most sophisticated .
Male and female associates work with small groups of four or five medical students , residents or practicing doctors enrolled in continuing education programs .
Women work in teams of two , first demonstrating an ideal doctor-patient interaction , beginning with a knock at the examination room door , through the initial handshake and on through the actual examination .
Next , the medical students themselves follow the process , from the door through the examination .
Ms. Saltzman and her fellow associates are mostly part-time workers .
They are often people who are used to being looked at in their other jobs _ as actors , dancers and models .
They are well-trained as associates , and apprenticed .
In a way , they 've donated their live bodies to science , for an hourly fee .
In New York City , women typically receive $ 175 for a three-hour session , and men usually make $ 150 for two hours .
Some , like Ms. Saltzman , work more than a dozen of the three-hour sessions each year .
Male associates function more as live models as a urologist guides the sessions , though the men do interact with the students by answering questions and explaining what is comfortable and what is not during the genital and rectal exams .
Not everyone can do it , said Robert Speller , an associate for 12 years .
`` Nude , and nude and examined are very different , '' he said .
For some associates , including Ms. Saltzman , the work brings in more than money .
Last month , she said , she taught a medical student who had never had a pelvic exam herself , and by the end of the session , the student was ready to make an appointment .
Tracey Wang , 23 , a second-year medical student , was impressed as well .
After a December session of pelvic and breast examinations at Jacobi Medical Center in the Bronx , Ms. Wang said with a mixture of relief and confidence , `` I thought it would be uncomfortable to be instructed from that position , but now I don n't see a better way of doing it . ''
Dr. Paula Stillman of the Lehigh Valley Health System in Pennsylvania agreed .
`` When I went to medical school , we made the same mistakes over and over again , '' said Dr. Stillman , who has worked with associates since the 1970s .
`` Even a lot of experienced physicians may not have felt an ovary .
When you watch someone doing a pelvic you can n't tell what they 're feeling .
The only way you can really tell is if the person you 're doing the exam on can tell you . ''
